**The magic of callbacks:**

The JavaScript array has a number of cool iteration methods, that all take a callback as a parameter, like forEach(), filter(), map() and many more.

In the following exercises we are first going to use these basic methods, to recap our knowledge about what they do, and then, we are going to implement the methods by our self, as if they did not already exist.

**1) Using existing functions that takes a callback as an argument**

Using the **filter** method:

Declare a JavaScript array and initialize it with some names (Lars, Jan, Peter, Bo, Frederik etc.). Use the filter method to create a new array with only names of length &lt;=3.

Using the **map** method:

Use the names-array created above, and, using its map method, create a new array with all names uppercased.

**2) Implement user defined functions that take callbacks as an argument**

Now, assume the array did not offer these two methods. Then we would have to implement them by our self.

Implement a function: myFilter(array, callback)that takes an array as the first argument, and a callback as the second and returns a new (filtered) array according to the code provided in the callback (that is with the same behaviour as the original filter method).

Test the method with the same array and callback as in the example with the original filter method.

Implement a function: myMap(array, callback)that, provided an array and a callback, provides the same functionality as calling the existing map method on an array.

Test the method with the same array and callback as in the example with the original map method.

**3) Using the Prototype property to add new functionality to existing objects**

_Every JavaScript function has a prototype property (this property is empty by default), and you can attach properties and methods on this_ **prototype** _property. You add methods and properties on an object&#39;s prototype property to make those methods and properties available to all instances of that Object. You can even implement (classless) inheritance hierarchies with this property._

The problem with our two user defined functions above (myFilter and myMap) is that they are not really attached to the Array Object. They are just functions, where we have to pass in both the array and the callback1.

Create a new version of the two functions (without the array argument) which you should add to the Array prototype property so they can be called on any array as sketched below:

var names = [&quot;Lars&quot;, &quot;Peter&quot;, &quot;Jan&quot;, &quot;Bo&quot;];

var newArray = names. **myFilter** (function(name) {…});

**4) More user defined functions with callbacks**

Implement a JavaScript function: handleNumArrays(na1,na2,callback);

**na1** and **na2** are both _numeric_ arrays, and you can assume that they have identical lengths.

The method should create a new array with the sums of the two arrays passed in. It should then call the callback with the new array as argument.

If called like this:

var a = [1,2,3];

var b = [1,2,3];

handleNumArrays(a,b,function(res){

    console.log(res.join(&quot;,&quot;));

})

It should produce this string:  &quot;2,4,6&quot;

Implement the function and test it with the following callbacks:

- The one given in the example above
- A callback that calculates the sum of all numbers in the array passed in
- A callback that multiplies each value in the array with 10 and displays all items comma separated.

**Learning with the debugger**

One of the things I have observed throughout the previous semester, is that much too many of you ask questions, which easily could have been answered if you had used the debugger.

You get five StudyPoints by repeating loudly - five times &quot; **The debugger is my friend**&quot; ;-)

You simply have to get used to the debugger (you could be requested to demo at the exam) and this goes for all development you do, not only JavaScript!

- When debugging client side code (or even hybrid apps running on your phone ;-) use the built in debugger in Chrome or whatever browser you are using.
- When debugging server side JavaScript, use the built in debugger in WebStorm or whatever IDE you are using

You can actually learn a lot from debugging your code.

Create a new JavaScript file in WebStorm and make a Node.js configuration to run and debug this file.

Add the following code to the file, and add a breakpoint to the last line. Debug the file.

**var**  **a** = {};
**var**  **b** = [];
**var**  **c** = **true** ;
**var**  **d** = **&quot;Hello World&quot;** ;
**var**  **e** = 123;
**var**  **f** = **new** Date();
**console**.log( **&quot;Add a breakpoint on me&quot;** );

Use the debug window to investigate the content of the six variables, and also all the other &quot;stuff&quot; not related to the six variables (this, \_\_dirname, everything in Global etc.)

You should spend at least 30 minutes on this exercise. For all the stuff you don&#39;t understand, ask Google or put a question (make sure to also answer questions) on the Q&amp;A site.
